{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 16:23:26.697911", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nNetwork / topology summary (relevant parts)\n- Two hosts: pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2/24) attached to leaf_router_0_0 (eth2: 10.0.0.1/24), and pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2/24) attached to leaf_router_0_1 (eth2: 10.0.1.1/24).\n- Two spines (spine_router_0_0 AS65100, spine_router_0_1 AS65101) peer with a super-spine (super_spine_router_0 AS65000) and with leaves.\n- Leaves are expected to advertise their /24 host subnets into EBGP to spines; spines should propagate them to super-spine and other spines.\n\nExecutive summary (high-level)\n- The network is partially functional: the 10.0.1.0/24 prefix (pc_0_1 / leaf_router_0_1) is being advertised and learned across the spines/super-spine.\n- The 10.0.0.0/24 prefix (pc_0_0 / leaf_router_0_0) is NOT visible outside leaf_router_0_0 — it is not present in spine or super-spine routing/BGP tables. As a result, other pods cannot reach 10.0.0.0/24.\n- Root cause: BGP neighbor configuration mismatch between the spines and leaf_router_0_0 (incorrect remote-AS configured on the spines for the leaf), causing the BGP sessions for that leaf to not form and the leaf’s prefix not to be propagated.\n- Secondary observation: pc_0_0 shows zero interface packet counters and active ping attempts to it from the test harness failed with \"Device ... is not running\" — indicating that the host may not be responsive/fully up. However, even if the host were up, the routing absence described above would prevent reachability from other pods.\n\nDetailed evidence and findings\n\n1) Host interface and traffic counters\n- pc_0_0:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24\n  - RX packets 0  bytes 0, TX packets 0  bytes 0 (no observed traffic)\n  - ip route: default via 10.0.0.1\n- pc_0_1:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.1.2/24\n  - RX packets 6 bytes 624, TX packets 6 bytes 476 (traffic seen)\n  - ip route: default via 10.0.1.1\n- leaf_router_0_0 eth2 (connected to pc_0_0): shows inet 10.0.0.1/24 but RX/TX packets are 0 — no traffic to/from that host was observed on the leaf.\n- leaf_router_0_1 eth2: shows packets (consistent with pc_0_1 traffic).\n\nInterpretation:\n- pc_0_0 (and its leaf-facing link) show no traffic; pc_0_1 and its leaf link show traffic. This suggests either pc_0_0 is down/unresponsive or traffic is not being forwarded/arriving. The ping tool attempts to reach pc_0_0 returned \"Device `10.0.0.2` is not running.\"\n\n2) BGP configuration mismatches (local config outputs)\n- leaf_router_0_0 configuration:\n  - \"router bgp 65800\" (leaf_0_0 AS = 65800)\n  - neighbors configured to spines: neighbor 172.16.0.4 remote-as 65100 and neighbor 172.16.0.8 remote-as 65101\n  - advertising network 10.0.0.0/24 locally\n- spine_router_0_0 configuration:\n  - \"router bgp 65100\"\n  - neighbors: neighbor 172.16.0.0 remote-as 65000, neighbor 172.16.0.5 remote-as 65200, neighbor 172.16.0.7 remote-as 65201\n    - Note: 172.16.0.5 is leaf_router_0_0's spine-facing IP, but spine expects that neighbor to be remote-as 65200 (NOT 65800).\n- spine_router_0_1 configuration:\n  - \"router bgp 65101\"\n  - neighbors: neighbor 172.16.0.2 remote-as 65000, neighbor 172.16.0.9 remote-as 65200, neighbor 172.16.0.11 remote-as 65201\n    - Note: 172.16.0.9 is leaf_router_0_0's other spine-facing IP, but spine expects remote-as 65200 (not 65800).\n\nConclusion from configs:\n- Both spine routers have an incorrect remote-as (65200) configured for the addresses that are actually leaf_router_0_0. leaf_router_0_0's AS is 65800. This AS mismatch will prevent BGP neighbor sessions from forming between the spines and leaf_router_0_0.\n\n3) BGP tables / route tables (selected outputs)\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP table:\n  - Displays its local network: 10.0.0.0/24 (installed locally with next-hop 0.0.0.0).\n- spine_router_0_0 BGP / routing:\n  - BGP table shows only 10.0.1.0/24 (learned via 172.16.0.7 / leaf_router_0_1)\n  - ip route shows a route for 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7; there is NO route for 10.0.0.0/24 on spine_router_0_0.\n- spine_router_0_1 BGP / routing:\n  - BGP table also shows 10.0.1.0/24 (learned via leaf_router_0_1); no 10.0.0.0/24 learned.\n- super_spine_router_0 BGP:\n  - Shows routes for 10.0.1.0/24 via its spine peers, but no 10.0.0.0/24.\n\nInterpretation:\n- 10.0.1.0/24 (leaf_router_0_1 → pc_0_1) propagated through spines and super-spine as expected; full visibility and typical path selection exist.\n- 10.0.0.0/24 (leaf_router_0_0 → pc_0_0) remains only local to leaf_router_0_0; it is not learned by spines or super-spine and therefore unreachable from other pods.\n\n4) Active ping tests from the test harness\n- Attempts to ping pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 via the provided ping tool failed with: \"Device `10.0.0.2` is not running.\" / \"Device `10.0.1.2` is not running.\"\n- The tool error suggests the test harness couldn't reach/execute pings on those device containers. This is a separate operational observation about the lab/test harness, but does not contradict the BGP observations.\n\nLocalization — which devices are implicated\n- Primary misconfiguration / fault devices:\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1: misconfigured remote-as for the neighbor IPs that correspond to leaf_router_0_0. This prevents the BGP sessions towards leaf_router_0_0 from establishing.\n  - Evidence: spine_router_0_0 config shows \"neighbor 172.16.0.5 remote-as 65200\" but leaf_router_0_0's AS is 65800. spine_router_0_1 shows \"neighbor 172.16.0.9 remote-as 65200\" but leaf_router_0_0 is AS65800.\n- Secondary / possibly affected device:\n  - pc_0_0: interface shows no packets and ping attempts reported \"Device ... is not running.\" It may be down/uninitialized inside the lab. Even if pc_0_0 were up, it would still be unreachable from the rest of the fabric due to the BGP propagation problem described above.\n\nRoot cause analysis (why reachability broken)\n- The immediate root cause: BGP neighbor AS mismatch between the spines and leaf_router_0_0. Because the spines are configured with the wrong remote-AS for leaf_router_0_0 (they expect AS65200), the EBGP sessions do not form. As a result leaf_router_0_0's advertised network 10.0.0.0/24 is not accepted/learned by the spine routers and therefore not propagated upward to super-spine nor sideways to other spines. This causes network-wide lack of visibility for 10.0.0.0/24.\n- The lack of traffic counters on pc_0_0 and on its leaf-facing interface is either a consequence of (a) the host is not up/inoperative, or (b) no traffic reaches the host because other routers do not have a route to its subnet. Both explanations fit the data; the BGP issue alone explains cross-pod reachability failure. The \"Device is not running\" ping-tool errors indicate the test harness could not interact with the host container.\n\nImpact statement\n- Cross-pod host reachability is asymmetric:\n  - pc_0_1 <-> pc_0_0: cannot reach 10.0.0.2 from the fabric because the route to 10.0.0.0/24 is missing from spines/super-spine.\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 (pc_0_1) is correctly propagated and reachable across the fabric.\n- Control-plane (BGP) visibility for leaf_router_0_0’s prefix is absent outside leaf_router_0_0, limiting any traffic destined to 10.0.0.0/24 from other pods.\n\nConfidence level\n- High confidence that the AS mismatch on spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 for leaf_router_0_0 is the principal cause of the missing 10.0.0.0/24 propagation (directly evidenced by configs and the absence of the prefix in spine/super-spine BGP/routing tables).\n- Moderate confidence that pc_0_0 itself may be down/unresponsive — the lab’s ping tool reported the device not running and the interface counters on the host and leaf show zero traffic. This may be a separate problem or simply a symptom (traffic not arriving because of BGP).\n\nKey artifacts / excerpts (evidence pointers)\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP AS: \"router bgp 65800\" and \"network 10.0.0.0/24\" (leaf is advertising 10.0.0.0 locally).\n- spine_router_0_0 config: \"neighbor 172.16.0.5 remote-as 65200\" (incorrect remote-as for leaf_router_0_0 which is AS 65800).\n- spine_router_0_1 config: \"neighbor 172.16.0.9 remote-as 65200\" (same incorrect remote-as).\n- spine BGP / routing: spines show 10.0.1.0/24 in their BGP table and routes; there is no 10.0.0.0/24 present on spines or super-spine.\n- Interface counters: pc_0_0 eth0 RX/TX = 0; leaf_router_0_0 eth2 RX/TX = 0. pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1 show traffic.\n- Ping tool errors: \"Device `10.0.0.2` is not running.\" / \"Device `10.0.1.2` is not running.\" (test harness-level observation).\n\nSummary / final statement\n- The primary anomaly is that leaf_router_0_0’s prefix (10.0.0.0/24) is not propagated beyond the leaf because BGP sessions between that leaf and both spine routers are not established due to misconfigured remote-AS values on the spine routers. This prevents cross-pod reachability to pc_0_0. Additionally, pc_0_0 shows no traffic and the test harness could not reach the device, so the host may also be offline; however even a live host would be unreachable from other pods until the BGP control-plane issue is resolved.\n\n(End of diagnostic report — no mitigation steps provided per request.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13105, "output_tokens": 5563, "total_tokens": 18668, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12032}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2880}}}
